HEADWORD: Theologue
<hw>The"o*logue</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. L.
<ets>theologus</ets>, Gr. <?/, and E. <ets>philologue</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A theologian.</def> <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ye gentle <qex>theologues</qex> of calmer kind.</q>
<rj><qau>Young.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He [Jerome] was the <qex>theologue</qex> -- and the word is
designation enough.</q> <rj><qau>I. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A student in a theological seminary.</def>
<altsp>[Written also <asp>theolog</asp>.]</altsp> <mark>[Colloq. U.
S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Theology</ent>⟦br⟧
